Sep 16 2008 	Wonderfully Different	Inn New York City is a unique experience and one that should not be missed. The accommodations in a converted townhouse are luxurious, the woodwork is beautiful and functional, and the amenities and staff exceptionally thoughtful. It would be the perfect place for a honeymoon or other romantic trip. This is not a good place for small children, and one must be able to climb stairs, as there are no elevators. If you need a break from standard hotel layout and furnishings, you will love the Inn. The location is on the upper east side, so it is not near the theater district, but it is a short walk to Lincoln center, central park, etc. We had no problem getting taxis in the neighborhood. There is no identifying sign outside, only the address on a small marquee over the front stoop. If you catch a taxi to get there, be sure to tell the driver that the block is between Broadway and West End.	
Sep 4 2008 	A Sanctuary!	What a wonderful stay we had at the Inn New York City, it was everything you read here at Trip Advisor and more.We were a party of 4, 2 women and 2 teenage girls booked in the Library Suite for 5 nights, August 19th - 24th.The Library Suite is on the top floor of the Inn, 2 interior flights up... from the moment we walked in the front door we felt like we were home. Elyn showed us up to our suite giving us a tour as we went. All the comforts of home abound in this gorgeous apartment with full kitchen, living room, beautiful dining area and charming bedroom with sun streaming in from the leaded glass skylights ~ We all loved it immediately!Our kitchen was well stocked with treats and breakfast items including fresh bagels, croissants, danishes, granola and assorted other pastries/pies/brownies which were replenished daily during our stay. We also found other snacks like cheeses and quiche in the refrigerator, various flavours of sodas and premium brand waters. A fresh fruit basket piled high with a variety of fruits - when we requested extra strawberries we soon had more than we knew what to do with!  There was also gourmet ground coffee which we enjoyed each morning, freshly perked as we read the paper that was quietly slipped under our door. The suite has a stove, oven, toaster oven and all the dishes, glassware, pots &amp; pans, cutlery, appliances and kitchen implements you could possible need to cook a meal. Behind two wood panels is the hidden laundry area with washer/.dryer/soaps and fabric softeners, bleach, iron etc... everything you would need for a longer stay.The suite itself was cheerful and bright with high ceilings, floral carpeting, granite countertops, leather furniture, fresh flowers, various artwork, photographs and of course shelves and shelves of books. We especially enjoyed the lovely &amp; large dining area where we had breakfast each day.Our bed was very comfortable with luxurious linens, also the queen size sofa bed in the living room was comfortable and was turned down for us each night while we were out at dinner or a show. It was lovely to come 'home' to find soft lighting and our beds prepared for us. We appreciated the pocket doors the closed off the living room from the rest of the suite - it separated us from the giggling teens who had their privacy.In the bedroom there was a lovely reading area with plush chair and ottoman by a cozy fireplace. We loved the whimsical decorations throughout the suite such as vintage luggage piled atop the wardrobe, large wooden propeller &amp; toboggan on the living room brick.There were plenty of luxurious towers and thick robes for each of us. Soaps, lotions, shampoos &amp; conditioners ever an electric shoe polisher in the bedroom, everything you could think of and more from umbrellas to first aid supplies was tucked away in the many cupboards and closets.The suite had a digital safe in the closet so we could lock up our valuables. We enjoyed the fact there was 2 televisions both with DVD player which we used often during our stay, borrowing from the Inn's collection of DVDs.We never heard a sound from the Inn hosts, staff or the other guests. The Inn New York City is a quiet respite from the craziness of the Big Apple. At times it was hard to believe that just out our door was this huge busy city we really felt like we were out in the country somewhere.The location of the Inn is fabulous, literally a 3 minute walk to the 72nd street subway and 1 stop away is Times Square. A 10 - 15 minute stroll has you at Central Park, we loved walking along Broadway with tons of shopping. We had meals in some wonderful little Italian restaurants on Broadway just minutes away. The Lincoln center movie AMC IMAX theatre is just a couple of blocks away as well.On 71st street there is a Cafe 71 shop with fresh bakery, pizzeria, paninis, salads, eat in or take out - we stopped there almost every day for something. Also, just by the subway station is Gray's Papaya for a quick (and cheap) bite to eat.We absolutely loved our stay with Ruth &amp; Elyn who made sure we were comfortable, safe, informed and rested. The housekeeping staff made everything gleam and our suite was spotless for us every day. Thank you Inn New York City we will be back again one day!	
