Mar 31 2008 	A residence for life's travellers	Living in the Opera Suite is akin to staying at the New York pied-à-terre of a graceful, thoughtful but racy Aunt who might have just popped out for an evening at the Met. You would not expect 24-hour room service from your virtual Aunt, and you will not find it at Inn New York City. But the merits of this elegant, genteel establishment far outweigh and compensate for the lack of facilities on offer in more renowned hotels.Ruth, the owner, operates a discrete and mannered refuge on the Upper West Side. There is no hotel sign and the Inn both looks and acts like a polished private residence. Residents and owner are quiet and take other guests into consideration: guests in the Opera Suite are asked not to play the baby grand piano after 10pm as the residents of the Spa suite upstairs similarly refrain from using their whirlpool tub after hours. Ruth asks for a discreet buzz on the button at the bottom of the stairs as you leave, so that the housekeeper can go into your room, and is willing to come at any time up to 9pm to light the fire in your bedroom. The décor is eclectic, part art deco, part French, part Edwardian, part 1950s floral chic: not quite over the top, but lovers of minimalism should look elsewhere. The Inn’s website has four lovely short films with piano music to illustrate each suite and the anticipation they create does not disappoint. There are heavy drapes and wooden New York shutters. The house feels loved, polished and personal. Aged graceful wooden cabinets have style, even if they creak a little with age, along with some floorboards. There is a small but full kitchen, again slightly aged but utterly charming and with more utensils than you will ever use during your visit, all of which looked as they had been gathered with care at antique markets. Fabrics have been chosen with care and thought, as have the individual pictures, lamps and soft furnishings. Opera magazines, old copies of magazines, sheet music, soft throws and books are scattered throughout the suite. Wardrobes and individually chosen armoires reinforce the feeling that this is a residence rather than a hotel. As the day fades into darkness, the Opera Suite comes alive with gorgeous dimmed lighting, and the fireplace. Make sure you take someone with you who can play the honey-tone baby grand, preferably slow jazz or melancholy chansons. The subway is one block away, taxis are always available as are private cars if you need one. The coffee shops, restaurants and upmarket boutiques on Columbus are a few minutes away, the Lincoln Centre and cinemas five minutes walk, Central Park no more than seven. Ruth fills the Suite each day with pastries, cakes, cheeses, crackers, chocolate, fruit and a myriad of little treats. Basic supplies are provided, more than enough for breakfast each day. If the weather is warm enough, you could breakfast outside on the shrub-filled terrace. An antique writing desk adds elegance to the room and the wifi worked flawlessly. The phone line is direct but there is voice mail and the line will ring through to the office is left to ring. Residents have their own keys and Ruth lays little traps of sweet jars throughout the hallway, to distract you from the flowers and the sherry she has left out.I saw no other residents during my stay but you do hear them. This is an old house, and it has all the gentle creaks and footfalls which that entails. The bathroom in the Opera Suite is on the small side and both it and the kitchen might eventually benefit from updating of fittings. But please, Ruth, keep the worn and loved elegance. I adored all the eclectic pots, plates and dishes in the kitchen cupboards and the bathroom was piled with soft towels, toiletries and robes. This is not the place to stay if you have children with you, even though there is also a sofa bed. If you leave the kids elsewhere and want a romantic, quiet, gentle time to concentrate with a loved one, eat out at leisure, take in something at Lincoln Centre and wander around on foot, this Suite is more than perfect. It is a residence for life’s travellers rather than tourists.	
