Jan 2 2008	Inn (heaven in) New York City	Inn New York City is extraordinary. I cannot recommend it highly enough. Its owners, Ruth and Elyn Mensch, could not be more welcoming and helpful. As Elyn put it the evening we checked in, they are as invisible or as available as their guests want them to be. We spent five days in the Library Suite from December 27, 2007 to Jan 1, 2008. The Suite has a lovely bedroom, a huge living room, high ceilings and stained glass skylights. It is full of visual surprises, including a sled, a propeller, a book-filled ladder and a displaced staircase cum towel stand. (This description does not do the Inn justice--please refer to the Inn's website. A picture = 1000 words.) in the Library Suite, there are, as you might expect, books everywhere; the shelves include current best-sellers and classics; the tissue box covers are book-shaped; an instruction manual on ironing for men is hidden in the ensuite laundry area. When we arrived, a quiche, bagels, brie and a bottle of pinot grigio were just some of the items waiting for us in our kitchen. There were chocolates on our pillows. Orange juice, more bagels and fresh pastries mysteriously appeared each day. Fresh fruit was always available in the front hallway. Housekeeping was unobtrusive and meticulous. The Inn has no street-front sign, which gives guests the pleasant illusion, when entering or exiting the building, of being residents rather than tourists. We loved the Inn's location. It is on New York's Upper West Side, just two blocks from Central Park, one block from the subway and five blocks from the Lincoln Center. The Inn is surrounded by cafes, restaurants and shopping. I cannot claim to know Ruth and Elyn Mensch but having spent five days at their inn, I think I can safely say that they know hospitality, interior design, good food and, as the Inn's name might suggest, whimsy.	
Jan 2 2008 	Cosy beautiful and welcoming	My husband booked Inn New York. I didn't really know where we were staying until we arrived and mine hostess showed us round. We stayed in the lovely Spa suite, complete with sauna, jacuzzi and walk-in shower. It also had a galley kitchen loaded with snacks and essentials, like tea bags and plenty of space to store everything. This is a beautiful guest house in a smart area of the city - there's a subway station at the top of the street and an express train can have you at Times Square in 5 minutes flat, or you can walk there in less than half an hour. Not only that, but you're less than 10 minutes' stroll from Central Park.We had a fantastic Christmas here. I was only disappointed that we had to leave. The owner was kind enough to not only let us store our baggage there after we'd checked out, but she also let us have the run of the Opera suite so that we could get changed before we went out for a meal.	
