Sep 11 2007 	This really is a special place	My mom and I were in New York for 5 nights (4 of them at the Inn New York City) for the US Open. We started the weekend before the Open doing tourist things around Manhattan and then spent the last 3 days going out to Flushing Meadows. This place was perfectly suited for both functions.I read all the reviews of this place before I booked and wondered if it could be as perfect as all these reviewers say. The answer is yes and no. My first reaction was that it didn’t quite live up to the reviews, but by the time I left, I had changed my mind. No place is perfect, but the positives of this place so far outweighed the negatives that it still deserves the 5 rating that I’ve given it. Reviews up to this point have few details. I’ll probably give too many! I’ll break it down into sections: location, problems, and amenities. LOCATION - I don’t think you can get any better than this!•The location is on 71st almost at West End. It dead ends at the beginning of Riverside Park. You get a great view of the Hudson at the end of the street. Because of the dead end, you don’t get much street traffic. •It’s a block to the 72nd subway where you can pick up a 1 local or a 2 or 3 express. Using the 2 or 3 trains gets you to midtown in minutes. We used it the express trains get to the 42nd street station and Penn Station with ease. •The subway station is at the junction of Amsterdam and Broadway which is really a thriving place – banks, shops, and fast food restaurants galore. It just seems so unreal to be in the middle of all of the hustle there and step onto 71st.•71st is absolutely gorgeous. It’s shaded by the buildings with lots of trees and little gardens and flower boxes by the residents. I didn’t realize how shaded it was until I walked over to 72nd which is much wider and sunnier.•There’s a 24-hour Duane Read a block away on 72nd.•Fairway Market is 3 blocks away. With the kitchen and accessories this place has, this is a real bonus and a significant way to cut down expenses. You feel like a local between shopping at Fairway and then preparing it in your brownstone kitchen.•Buttercup Bake Shop is a couple of blocks away if you are craving cupcakes. The vanilla butter cream were great; the red velvet not so great.•We picked up the M5 bus uptown at West End and 72nd and, man, was that an incredible drive. You have Riverside Park to the west with the Hudson and gorgeous brownstones on the east for over 30 blocks. This was one of the highlights of our trip.PROBLEMS•The toilet paper is really thin. I know this sounds picky, but you would expect something nicer at a place like this so concerned with the details.•The towels were so worn they were threadbare. They were huge, though, so you can tell that there was care made in the decision to use them. They just need to be replaced.•You can hear the guests walk around upstairs. There’s no creaking of the floors (that will drive me away from a place), so it wasn’t that bad.•The shower head is pretty but not very functional. On the positive side, the hot water comes out instantly and is plentiful.•The bed is lumpy, but I don’t see how they could replace it. You couldn’t get a mattress down the staircase without taking the staircase out. My mom suggested maybe a foam mattress cover would even out the bumps.AMENITIES•TV with the full selection (through 300 something) of digital channels including HBO•2 distinct living areas in the Vermont Suite which can become 2 bedrooms: bedroom with queen bed and bath downstairs and living room with sofa bed and kitchen upstairs.•No street noise•Soft feather pillows even with the sofa bed•The owner is wonderful. She is there as much or as little as you need her. •Fresh flowers both upstairs and downstairs•Phone with a direct number, free local calls, and voicemail•There is wood every where! The antiques in this place give it such a beautiful touch.•You really feel like you are coming home every night. We came in one night at the same time as the guy at the same level next door. •The a/c is in a window, but it’s strong! You can move the airflow where ever you want it.•The sheets are so soft both on the queen bed and the sofa bed.•There are lamps and lights every where. You can tell that it’s intentionally set up for many reading spaces.•The amount of food included every day is amazing. I tried making a list of all the different choices and stopped at 20 leaving out plenty. We made breakfast every day out of it plus the occasional lunch, part of dinner, and dessert. It cut our expenses down significantly which helped with the price of the room.•We awoke daily to that day’s New York Times.•The kitchen was smaller than I expected, but it is so well planned. We made a few meals actual meals in it boiling corn, eggs, etc. My mom is on a strict low sodium diet, so we cooked in as many meals as we could to control her sodium intake. I know NYC is famous for its restaurants, but there is something so pleasing to come home and enjoy a leisurely dinner bonding over the day’s events. This kitchen and the beautiful drop-leaf table really allow you to do that.•The sofa bed was really comfortable – almost to the point of being like a real bed.This place is truly like having your own beautifully furnished apartment with so many extras in an incredible location. I know I’m forgetting so many things because it seemed like every where we turned there was yet another wow! reaction. I’ve decided that I want to come back next year and have already started looking for another perfect place. Since I started searching so late this time, I thought I could find a better place that was booked at the time. I have not been able to find anything that can equal the combination of the amenities at the Inn, the beauty and accessibility of the UWS location, and the reasonable price.	
